<h3>Question 2</h3>
<div><p><p>Define normal distribution. What are the main chracteristics of normal distribution? Extruded plastic rods are automatically cut into length 5 inches. Actul length are normally distributed about a mean of  5 inches and their standard deviation is 0.05 inches. (i) What propotion of rods exceed tolerance limits of 4.9 inches to 5.1 inches? (ii) Proportion of rods having tolerance rod which is greater than 6.5 inches.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A probability distribution that is symmetric around its mean is called a normal distribution. This indicates that data that are closer to the mean occur more frequently than data that are farther from the mean. This distribution is frequently referred to as the &#8220;bell curve&#8221; due to its bell-like appearance. A normal distribution is a continuous distribution that is frequently used in statistics, and many natural events roughly follow it.</p>
<p>The probability density function of a normal distribution is given by:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$f(x) = \frac{{1}}{{\sigma \sqrt{{2\pi}}}} e^{{-\frac{{(x &#8211; \mu)^2}}{{2\sigma^2}}}}$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>where:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span></span> is a variable,</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">μ</span></span> is the mean of the distribution,</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">σ</span></span> is the standard deviation, and</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">σ<sup>2</sup></span></span> is the variance.</li>
</ul>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-s">​<strong>Numerical part</strong></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>Length = 5 inches<br />
Standard deviation (σ) = 0.05  inches<br />
Mean (μ) = 5  inches</p>
<p>(i) Proportion of rods that exceed tolerance limit of 4.9 inches to 5.1 inches</p>
<p>a) Calculating z -scores</p>
<p>$$<br />
Z_{{4.9}} = \frac{{X &#8211; \mu}}{{\sigma}} = \frac{{4.9 &#8211; 5}}{{0.05}} = -2<br />
$$<br />
$$<br />
Z_{{5.1}} = \frac{{X &#8211; \mu}}{{\sigma}} = \frac{{5.1 &#8211; 5}}{{0.05}} = 2<br />
$$</p>
<p>from table:</p>
<p>$$<br />
P(Z &lt; 2) = 0.9772<br />
$$<br />
$$<br />
P(Z &lt; -2) = 1 &#8211; 0.9772 = 0.0228<br />
$$</p>
<p>Proportion of rods within tolerance limits:<br />
$$<br />
P(4.9 &lt; X \leq 5.1) = P(Z &lt; 2) &#8211; P(Z &lt; -2)<br />
$$<br />
$$<br />
= 0.9772 &#8211; 0.0228 = 0.9544<br />
$$</p>
<p>Again, proportion of rods that exceed tolerance (i.e., outside 4.9 to 5.1):</p>
<p>$$<br />
P(X &lt; 4.9 \text{ or } X &gt; 5.1) = 1 &#8211; P(4.9 &lt; X \leq 5.1)<br />
$$<br />
$$<br />
= 1 &#8211; 0.9544 = 0.0456<br />
$$</p>
<p>(ii) Proportion of rods having length greater than 6.5 inches</p>
<p>$$<br />
Z_{{6.5}} = \frac{{6.5 &#8211; 5}}{{0.05}} = 30<br />
$$</p>
<p>Since the z -score is extremely high, meaning that area to the right of Z = 6.5  is approximately  0,</p>
<p>$$<br />
P(X &gt; 6.5) \approx 0<br />
$$</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 3</h3>
<div><p><p>Diffrence between correlation and regression analysis. Raw materials are used in the production od synthesis and fiber are stored in a place which has no humidity control. Measurement of relative humidity in the storage place and the moisture content of a sampleof a raw materials (both in percentage) on 10 days yeilds the following results.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-43746" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/table-.drawio.png" alt="" width="782" height="131"></p>
<ol>
<li>Compute correlation coefficiet between humidity and moisture content and interpret the result.</li>
<li>Find the regression equation of moisture content on humudity.</li>
<li>Estimate the moisture content if humudity is 45%</li>
<li>Interpreat the value of regression coefficient.</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Difference between correlation analysis and regression analysis is given below:</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 312px;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 50.7722%; text-align: center; height: 24px;"><strong>Correlation Analysis</strong>:</td>
<td style="width: 49.2278%; height: 24px; text-align: center;"><strong>Regression Analysis</strong>:</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 72px;">
<td style="width: 50.7722%; text-align: center; height: 72px;">It evaluates the degree to which two variables have a linear relationship and its direction.</td>
<td style="width: 49.2278%; height: 72px; text-align: center;">It is used to forecast a variable&#8217;s value by using the value of another variable as a guide. Between independent (predictor) and dependent (response) variables, it creates a cause-and-effect relationship.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 144px;">
<td style="width: 50.7722%; text-align: center; height: 144px;">A strong relationship is shown by values around 1 or -1, whereas a weak relationship is indicated by values near 0. The correlation coefficient, often known as r, is a number between -1 and 1.</td>
<td style="width: 49.2278%; height: 144px; text-align: center;">An equation describing the link is provided via regression, enabling predictions.</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 72px;">
<td style="width: 50.7722%; text-align: center; height: 72px;">Correlation just shows how much two variables move together; it does not prove causation.</td>
<td style="width: 49.2278%; height: 72px; text-align: center;">The rate at which the dependent variable changes for every unit change in the independent variable is represented by the regression coefficient.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p><strong>Numerical part</strong></p>
<p>given,</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-43746" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/table-.drawio.png" alt="" width="782" height="131"></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\bar{x} = \frac{\sum x}{n} = \frac{446}{10} = 44.6$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\bar{y} = \frac{\sum y}{n} = \frac{99}{10} = 9.9$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-43747" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/correlation.drawio.png" alt="" width="663" height="559"></p>
<p>i. <strong> Calculating the Correlation Coefficient <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">r</span></span>:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$r = \frac{\sum (x &#8211; \bar{x})(y &#8211; \bar{y})}{\sqrt{\sum (x &#8211; \bar{x})^2 \cdot \sum (y &#8211; \bar{y})^2}}$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$r = \frac{113.6}{\sqrt{942.4 \times 54.9}}$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$r = 0.4994$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>ii.  <strong>Finding the Regression Equation of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y</span></span> on <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span></span>:<br />
</strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Slope <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b </span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$b = \frac{\sum (x &#8211; \bar{x})(y &#8211; \bar{y})}{\sum (x &#8211; \bar{x})^2} = \frac{113.6}{942.4}= 0.1205$$<br />
</span></span></span><br />
<span style="text-decoration: underline;">Intercept </span><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">a</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$ a = \bar{y} &#8211; b \bar{x} = 9.9 &#8211; (0.1205 \times 44.6) = 4.524$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>by formula and value of a on solving we get regression eqn as</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y = 4.524 + 0.121x</span></span></span></p>
<p>iii.<strong> Estimating Moisture Content if Humidity is 45%:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$y = 4.524 + 0.121 \times 45 = 9.95$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>So, the estimated moisture content if humidity is 45% is approximately <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">9.95%</span></span>.</p>
<p>iv. <strong>Interpretation of the Regression Coefficient</strong>:</p>
<p>The regression coefficient <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">b=0.121</span></span> suggests that for each 1% increase in humidity, the moisture content increases by approximately 0.121%.</p>
</div>
<h2>SECTION B: Attempt any EIGHT questions.</h2><h3>Question 4</h3>
<div><p><p>What is sampling? Explain the main purpose of sampling. Describe briefly stratified sampling.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Sampling</strong> is the practice of choosing a subset of people, things, or observations from a broader population in order to draw conclusions or estimate the population as a whole. Researchers utilize sampling to collect data from a smaller group that is representative of the wider population rather than examining the entire population, which can be expensive and time-consuming.</p>
<p>The main purposes of sampling include:</p>
<ol style="list-style-type: lower-roman;">
<li><strong>Cost Efficiency:</strong><br />
Gathering data from a whole population is frequently difficult or prohibitively expensive. Researchers can obtain enough data through sampling without having to pay a lot of money.</li>
<li><strong>Time Efficiency:</strong><br />
Data from a sample can be analyzed and decisions made more quickly than data from the complete population because sample data collection is typically faster.</li>
<li><strong>Accuracy and Precision:</strong><br />
Compared to attempting to measure the entire population, well-designed sampling techniques can yield results that are more accurate and precise.</li>
<li><strong>Estimation:</strong><br />
Using sample statistics, researchers can estimate population parameters (such as variance and mean) through sampling. It makes it possible for researchers to extrapolate results from the sample to the entire population.</li>
<li><strong>Manageability:</strong><br />
The analysis is easier to handle and the complexity of data collection is decreased when working with a smaller selection of data.</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Stratified sampling</strong> is the population separated into discrete subgroups or strata based on shared attributes (e.g., age, gender, economic level).The main steps involved in stratified sampling are:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Identify Strata</li>
<li>Sample Selection</li>
<li>Combine Samples</li>
</ul>
</div>
<h3>Question 5</h3>
<div><p><p>What do you understand by measurement of dispersion? Two batsman A and B made the following runs in a series of cricket matches.</p>
<div class="table_wrapper"><table>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>A</td>
<td>19</td>
<td>25</td>
<td>10</td>
<td>30</td>
<td>18</td>
<td>28</td>
<td>50</td>
<td>33</td>
<td>28</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>B</td>
<td>5</td>
<td>75</td>
<td>80</td>
<td>17</td>
<td>38</td>
<td>40</td>
<td>90</td>
<td>0</td>
<td>55</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Who is more consistent player? Give your statistical reasoning.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Measurement of Dispersion</strong>:<br />
The term &#8220;measurement of dispersion&#8221; describes statistical methods for characterizing a dataset&#8217;s variability or spread. It displays the degree to which a dataset&#8217;s values deviate from the mean (average). Standard deviation, variance, and range are common metrics used to quantify dispersion. The data points are more consistent when they are closer to the mean, as indicated by a lower dispersion.</p>
<p>given,</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 57px;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">A</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">19</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">25</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">10</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">30</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">18</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">28</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">50</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">33</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 24px;">28</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 33px;">
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">B</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">5</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">75</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">80</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">17</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">38</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">40</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">90</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">0</td>
<td style="width: 10%; height: 33px;">55</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Calculating the Mean for each player :</p>
<p>$$mean f A = \frac{{19+25+10+30+18+28+50+33+28}}{{9}} = \frac{{241}}{{9}} = 26.78$$</p>
<p>$$mean f B = \frac{{5+75+80+17+38+40+90+0+55}}{{9}}$$</p>
<p>$$= \frac{{400}}{{9}} = 44.44$$</p>
