<td style="width: 38.2487%; text-align: center; height: 24px;"><span class="base"><span class="mrel"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">0 </span><span class="mbin">− </span><span class="mord">44.44</span><span class="mclose">)<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span>=1975.14</span></span></td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 13.3847%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">28</td>
<td style="width: 12.8404%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">55</td>
<td style="width: 35.5262%; text-align: center; height: 24px;"><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">28 </span><span class="mbin">− </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">26.78</span><span class="mclose">)<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2 </span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">= 1.49</span></span></td>
<td style="width: 38.2487%; text-align: center; height: 24px;"><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">55 </span><span class="mbin">− </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">44.44</span><span class="mclose">)<sup><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></sup></span><span class="mrel">=</span></span>111.53</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p><strong>Sum of squared deviations for A i.e Σ(A &#8211; mean of A)<sup>2</sup></strong> :</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">60.53 + 3.17 + 281.52 + 10.37 + 77.06 + 1.49 + 539.15 + 38.69 + 1.49 =1013.47</span></span></span></p>
<p>Divide by <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">n − 1 = 8</span></span> and take the square root:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\text{Standard Deviation of A} = \sqrt{\frac{1013.47}{8}} = \sqrt{126.68} = 11.26$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><strong>Sum of squared deviations for B i.e Σ(B &#8211; mean of B)<sup>2</sup> :</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">1555.54 + 933.14 + 1264.31 + 753.46 + 41.47 + 19.71 + 2075.95 + 1975.14 + 111.53 = 8730.25</span></span></span></p>
<p>Divide by  <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">n − 1 = 8</span></span> and take the square root:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\text{Standard Deviation of B} = \sqrt{\frac{8730.25}{8}}= \sqrt{1091.28} = 33.04$$</span></span></span></p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Standard Deviation of A</strong> ≈ 11.26</li>
<li><strong>Standard Deviation of B</strong> ≈ 33.04</li>
</ul>
<p>Statistically speaking, <strong>Batsman A</strong> is the more reliable player because his performance deviates less from the mean than Batsman B&#8217;s due to his lower standard deviation.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 6</h3>
<div><p><p>Define skewness and kurtosis. The first four moments about mean are 0, 14.75, 39.75 and 152.31. Compute skewness and kurtosis and interprete the results.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Skewness</strong> is a metric used to quantify how asymmetrical a real-valued random variable&#8217;s probability distribution is. A distribution may be:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Equivalent</span> (Skewness = 0)</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Skewed positively</span> (right-skewed, skewness &gt; 0): The right side&#8217;s tail is longer.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Negatively Skewed </span> (Left-skewed, Skewness &lt; 0) : The left side&#8217;s tail is longer.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Formula for Skewness (γ1)</strong>:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$Skewness = \frac{\mu_3}{\sigma^3}$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-s">​where <span class="katex-mathml">μ<sub>3 </sub></span>is the third moment about the mean, and <span class="katex-mathml">σ\</span> is the standard deviation (square root of the second moment about the mean).</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><strong>Kurtosis:<br />
</strong>A measure of the probability distribution&#8217;s &#8220;tailedness&#8221; is called kurtosis. In contrast to a normal distribution, it indicates whether the distribution has heavy or light tails. Kurtosis types include:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Mesokurtic</span>: Shape of a normal distribution (Kurtosis ≈ 3).</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Leptokurtic</span>: thicker tails and a sharper peak (Kurtosis &gt; 3).</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Platykurtic</span> (Kurtosis &lt; 3): lighter tails and a flatter apex.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Formula for Kurtosis (γ2)</strong>:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$Kurtosis = \frac{\mu_4}{\sigma^4}$$</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">μ<sub>4</sub></span></span> is the fourth moment about the mean.</p>
<div class="group/conversation-turn relative flex w-full min-w-0 flex-col agent-turn">
<div class="flex-col gap-1 md:gap-3">
<div class="flex max-w-full flex-col flex-grow">
<div class="min-h-8 text-message flex w-full flex-col items-end gap-2 whitespace-normal break-words [.text-message+&amp;]:mt-5" dir="auto" data-message-author-role="assistant" data-message-id="60018c92-8f41-4f2c-9ade-d852d0bce737" data-message-model-slug="gpt-4o">
<div class="flex w-full flex-col gap-1 empty:hidden first:pt-[3px]">
<div class="markdown prose w-full break-words dark:prose-invert dark">
<p><strong>Numerical part </strong></p>
<p>given,</p>
<p><strong>First four moments about the mean</strong>:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li style="list-style-type: none;">
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">μ<sub>1 </sub>= 0</span></span></li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">μ<sub>2 </sub>= 14.75 </span></span>(variance)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">μ<sub>3</sub> = 39.75</span></span></li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">μ<sub>4 </sub>= 152.31</span></span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<p>now,</p>
<ol style="list-style-type:decimal;">
<li><strong>Standard Deviation</strong> <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(σ)</span></span>:
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex">$$<br />
\sigma = \sqrt{\mu_2} = \sqrt{14.75} = 3.84<br />
$$</p>
<p></span></span></li>
<li><strong>Skewness</strong> <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(γ<sub>1</sub>)</span></span>:
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$ \text{Skewness} = \frac{\sigma^3}{\mu^3} = \frac{(3.84)^3}{39.75} = \frac{56.72}{39.75} = 0.70$$<br />
</span></span></span></li>
<li><strong>Kurtosis</strong> <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">(γ<sub>2</sub>)</span></span>:
<p>$$<br />
\text{Kurtosis} = \frac{\mu_4}{\sigma^4} = \frac{152.31}{(3.84)^4} = \frac{152.31}{330.43} = 0.46<br />
$$</li>
</ol>
<h3>Interpretation of Results</h3>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><strong>Skewness (0.70) : </strong>The distribution has a slight right-hand tail, suggesting a few values that are higher than the mean, indicating that it is positively skewed.</li>
<li><strong>Kurtosis (0.46) : </strong>This distribution is platykurtic, which means it has lighter tails and a flatter peak than a normal distribution, because the kurtosis is less than 3.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<h3>Question 7</h3>
<div><p><p>What are partition values? From the following distributionof scores 200 students of a college :</p>
<div class="table_wrapper"><table>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Scores</td>
<td>30-40</td>
<td>40-50</td>
<td>50-60</td>
<td>60-70</td>
<td>70-80</td>
<td>80-90</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Number of students</td>
<td>14</td>
<td>50</td>
<td>60</td>
<td>45</td>
<td>20</td>
<td>11</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Compute (i) the minimum scores obtained by top 10% students (ii) the range of middle 60 % students.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Points that split a distribution into equal portions are known as partition values. Typical values for partitions include:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Quartiles (four equal portions of data)</li>
<li>Deciles (ten equal pieces of data)</li>
<li>Data is divided into 100 equal portions using percentiles.</li>
</ul>
<p>In order to determine precise partition values for the top 10% and middle 60% of students, we are working with percentiles in this problem.</p>
<div class="table_wrapper" style="overflow-x:auto;"><table style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; height: 72px;">
<tbody>
<tr style="height: 24px;">
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">Scores</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">30-40</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">40-50</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">50-60</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">60-70</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">70-80</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 24px;">80-90</td>
</tr>
<tr style="height: 48px;">
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">Number of students</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">14</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">50</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">60</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">45</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">20</td>
<td style="width: 14.2857%; text-align: center; height: 48px;">11</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Total number of students <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">N=200</span></span>.</p>
<p>i.  <strong>The lowest scores that the top 10% of students received</strong><br />
The 90th percentile (<span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">P<sub>90</sub></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>) is calculated to determine the score that represents the top 10% of students. since the top 10% starts from the 90th percentile and above.</p>
<p>The formula to calculate the position of a percentile <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">P<sub>k</sub></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{k}} =\frac{{k}}{{100}} \times N$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">k = 90</span></span> and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">N = 200</span></span>.</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{90}} = \frac{{90}}{{100}} \times 200 = 180$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>Therefore, in order to establish the minimum score for the top 10%, we require the 180th score.</p>
<p>To determine where the 180th score falls, let&#8217;s compute the cumulative frequency:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>Cumulative frequency up to 30-40 = 14</li>
<li>Cumulative frequency up to 40-50 = 14 + 50 = 64</li>
<li>Cumulative frequency up to 50-60 = 64 + 60 = 124</li>
<li>Cumulative frequency up to 60-70 = 124 + 45 = 169</li>
<li>Cumulative frequency up to 70-80 = 169 + 20 = 189</li>
</ul>
<p>The 180th score falls in the 70-80 class interval.</p>
<p>To be precise, we can use linear interpolation within this interval. Let:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">L = 70</span></span> (lower limit of the 70-80 class)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">F = 169</span></span> (cumulative frequency up to 60-70)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">f = 2</span></span> (frequency of the 70-80 class)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">C = 10</span></span> (class width)</li>
</ul>
<p>Using the percentile formula within the interval:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{90}} = L + \frac{{180 &#8211; F}}{{f}} \times C$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{90}} = 70 + \frac{{180 &#8211; 169}}{{20}} \times 10$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{90}} = 70 + \frac{{11}}{{20}} \times 10$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{90}} = 70 + 5.5 = 75.5$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>As a result, the top 10% of pupils receive a minimum score of roughly 75.5.</p>
<p>ii.  <strong> The middle 60% of students&#8217; range</strong><br />
Between the 20th percentile (P<sub>20</sub>) and the 80th percentile (P<sub>80</sub>), the middle 60% of students are located.<span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{20}} = \frac{{20}}{{100}} \times 200 = 40$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>The 40th score falls within the 40-50 interval.</p>
<p>Using interpolation:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">L = 40</span></span> (lower limit of the 40-50 class)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">F = 14</span></span> (cumulative frequency up to 30-40)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">f = 50</span></span> (frequency of the 40-50 class)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">C = 10</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{20}} = L + \frac{{40 &#8211; F}}{{f}} \times C$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{20}} = 40 + \frac{{40 &#8211; 14}}{{50}} \times 10$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{20}} = 40 + \frac{{26}}{{50}} \times 10$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{20}} = 40 + 5.2 = 45.2$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>So, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">P<sub>20</sub> <span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mrel">≈</span></span></span> 45.2</span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​Calculating <span class="katex-mathml">P<sub>80</sub></span>​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{80}} = \frac{{80}}{{100}} \times 200 = 160$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>The 160th score falls in the 60-70 interval.</p>
<p>Using interpolation:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">L = 60</span></span>(lower limit of the 60-70 class)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">F = 124</span></span> (cumulative frequency up to 50-60)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">f = 45</span></span> (frequency of the 60-70 class)</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">C = 10</span></span></li>
</ul>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{80}} = L +  \frac{{160 &#8211; F}}{{f}} \times C$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{80}} = 60 + frac{{160 &#8211; 124}}{{45}} \times 10$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{80}} = 60 + \frac{{36}}{{45}} \times 10$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P_{{80}} = 60 + 8 = 68$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>So, <span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="msupsub"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><sub><span class="vlist"><span class="sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight"><span class="mord mtight">80</span></span></span></sub><span class="vlist-s">​ </span></span></span></span></span><span class="mrel">≈ </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">68</span></span></span></span>.</p>
<p>Hence, Minimum score for the top 10% of students approximately 75.5 and range of middle 60% of students approximately 45.2 to 68.</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 8</h3>
<div><p><p>Define mutually exclusive events and independent events in probability. A problem of mathematics is given to three students, A, B and C whose chances of solving the problem are in ratio 2 : 3 : 5. Find the probability that (i) all of them solve the problem. (ii) none of them solve the problem. (iii) the problem will be solved.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p><strong>Mutually Exclusive Events</strong>:<br />
When two events cannot happen simultaneously, they are said to be mutually exclusive (or discontinuous). Put otherwise, the occurrence of one event eliminates the likelihood of the other occurring.<br />
Calculated Representation: In the event that A and B are mutually exclusive, then P(A and B)=P(A∩B)=0<br />
For instance, &#8220;getting heads&#8221; and &#8220;getting tails&#8221; are mutually incompatible outcomes of flipping a coin since they cannot occur simultaneously.</p>
<p><strong>Independent Events</strong>:<br />
Two events are considered independent if the likelihood of one happening is unaffected by the occurrence of another. Stated differently, knowing the result of one event does not reveal the outcome of another.<br />
Calculated Representation: In the scenario when A and B are independent, P(A and B)=P(A)×P(B)<br />
Example: The outcome of the first roll of two dice is unrelated to the outcome of the second roll. One roll&#8217;s result has no bearing on the other&#8217;s result.</p>
<p>Given probabilities for A, B, and C are 2:3:5.<br />
$$<br />
P(A) = \frac{{2}}{{10}}, \quad P(B) = \frac{{3}}{{10}}, \quad P(C) = \frac{{5}}{{10}}<br />
$$</p>
<p>i. Probability that all solve the problem:<br />
$$<br />
P(A \cap B \cap C) = P(A)P(B)P(C) = \frac{{2}}{{10}} \times \frac{{3}}{{10}} \times \frac{{5}}{{10}} = 0.03<br />
$$</p>
<p>ii. Probability that none solves the problem:<br />
$$<br />
P(none) = (1 &#8211; P(A))(1 &#8211; P(B))(1 &#8211; P(C)) = (1 &#8211; \frac{{2}}{{10}})(1 &#8211; \frac{{3}}{{10}})(1 &#8211; \frac{{5}}{{10}}) = 0.504<br />
$$</p>
<p>iii. Probability that at least one solves the problem:<br />
$$<br />
P(at least one) = 1 &#8211; P(none) = 1 &#8211; 0.504 = 0.496<br />
$$</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 9</h3>
<div><p><p>Define Baye’s theorem. Store A, B and C have 100, 75 and 50 employees and, respectively 70, 60 and 50 percent of these are women. Registration are equally likely among all employees regardless of sex. One employee resigns, and this is woman. What is the probability that she works in store B?</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>A key theorem in probability theory, Bayes&#8217; theorem explains how to update a hypothesis&#8217;s probability in light of fresh data. It offers a method for computing conditional probabilities in mathematics.</p>
<p><strong>Formula for Bayes&#8217; Theorem</strong><br />
The Bayes theorem can be expressed as follows given two events, A and B, where A has already happened:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist"><span class="mclose">P(A|B) = <span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span>∣<span class="mord mathnormal">A</span>).<span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">A</span>) / <span class="mord mathnormal">P</span><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord mathnormal">B</span>)</span></span><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>where<br />
<strong>P(A∣B)</strong>:  is the posterior probability, or the likelihood that A will occur in light of B&#8217;s occurrence.<br />
<strong>P(B∣A)</strong>: Likelihood, or the chance that B will happen if A is true.<br />
<strong>P(A)</strong>: Prior probability, or the initial likelihood of A before any supporting data is taken into account.<br />
<strong>P(B)</strong>: The overall probability of B, or the marginal probability.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration: underline;"><strong>Numerical part</strong></span></p>
<p>given,<br />
Stores A, B, and C have 70%, 60%, and 50% women respectively.</p>
<p>P(woman | A) = 0.7,<br />
P(woman | B) = 0.6,<br />
P(woman | C) = 0.5</p>
<p>$$P(A) = \frac{{100}}{{225}} = 0.444,<br />
P(B) = \frac{{75}}{{225}} = 0.333,<br />
P(C) = \frac{{50}}{{225}} = 0.222<br />
$$</p>
<p>Total probability of selecting a woman:</p>
<p>$$P(woman) = P(woman| A)P(A) + P(woman| B)P(B) + P(woman| C)P(C)$$</p>
<p>$$= 0.7 \frac{{100}}{{225}} + 0.6 \frac{{75}}{{225}} + 0.5\frac{{50}}{{225}} = 0.622<br />
$$</p>
<p>Probability of selecting from B given woman:<br />
$$<br />
P(B|woman) = \frac{{P(woman|B) P(B)}}{{P(woman)}}<br />
= \frac{{0.6 \times 0.333}}{{0.622}}<br />
= 0.321<br />
$$</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 10</h3>
<div><p><p>Under what condition binomial probability distribution. Five unbaised coins are tossed 100 times and the following results were obtained.</p>
<div class="table_wrapper"><table>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>No of heads</td>
<td>0</td>
<td>1</td>
<td>2</td>
<td>3</td>
<td>4</td>
<td>5</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Frequency</td>
<td>5</td>
<td>24</td>
<td>35</td>
<td>22</td>
<td>10</td>
<td>4</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<p>Fit the binomial distribution.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>In order to fit a binomial distribution to the data, we must first ascertain whether the data is binomial and then identify the parameters of the binomial distribution, specifically n and p.</p>
<p>The following circumstances apply to a binomial distribution:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li>n is a set number of trials; as there are five coins in this instance, n=5.</li>
<li>Success (head) or failure (tail) are the two possible outcomes of each trial.</li>
<li>For every try, the chance of success, p, remains constant.</li>
<li>They are separate trials.</li>
</ul>
<p>This situation satisfies the requirements for a binomial distribution as each coin flip is independent and the likelihood of receiving heads should be constant. Estimating the probability p of getting a head on a single throw and using it is the aim.</p>
<p><strong>Numerical part</strong></p>
<p>The total number of coin tosses (trials) is 5 × 100 = 500 since 5 unbiased coins are tossed 100 times.</p>
<p>The sum of the products of frequencies with the corresponding number of heads is the total number of heads observed, which is 5×100=500.</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Total heads </span></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mbin">×</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">5</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">1</span><span class="mbin">×</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">24</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">2</span><span class="mbin">×</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">35</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">3</span><span class="mbin">×</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">22</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">4</span><span class="mbin">×</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">10</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">5</span><span class="mbin">×</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">4</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Total heads </span></span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">0</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">24</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">70</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">66</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">40</span><span class="mclose">)</span><span class="mbin">+</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mopen">(</span><span class="mord">20</span><span class="mclose">)</span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="base"><span class="mrel"><span class="mord text"><span class="mord">Total heads </span></span>= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">220</span></span></p>
<p>So, the probability of getting a head on a single toss is:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$p = \frac{{Total heads}}{{Total tosses}} = \frac{{220}}{{500}} = 0.44$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>Using <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">n = 5 </span></span>and <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">p = 0.44</span></span>, the probability of observing <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span></span> heads in 5 coin tosses follows a binomial probability mass function:</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-43685 aligncenter" src="https://hamrocsit.com/wp-content/uploads/2024/10/formula.drawio.png" alt="" width="196" height="62"></p>
<p>For each number of heads <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x=0,1,2,3,4,5</span></span> the expected frequency can be calculated as:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml"> </span></span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">Expected Frequency = 100×P(X=x)</span></span></span></p>
<p>where <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">P(X=x)</span></span> is the probability of observing <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span></span> heads.</p>
<p>The calculations for each <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span></span> will use the binomial formula above, and rounding each result to whole numbers will yield the expected frequencies for comparison with the observed frequencies.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
<h3>Question 11</h3>
<div><p><p>Define poission probability distribution. Cars arrive at a petrol station at an average rate of 3 per minute. Assuming that the cars arrive at random, find the probability that (a) no cars arrive during a particular minute. (b) at least one car arrive during a particular minute (c) four cars arriving per 2 minutes.</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>The amount of events that take place within a predetermined time or space span when they occur independently and at a known constant average rate is modeled by the Poisson probability distribution. The following formula is used to determine the likelihood of seeing x events during a specified time frame:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P(X = x) = \frac{{e^{{-\lambda}} \cdot \lambda^x}}{{x!}}$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>where:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">λ </span></span>is the average rate of occurrence (mean number of events per interval),</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">e </span></span> is the base of the natural logarithm (approximately equal to 2.718),</li>
<li><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span></span> is the number of occurrences (events) in the interval.</li>
</ul>
<p>Since autos arrive at an average speed of three per minute in this scenario, λ=3 for intervals of one minute.</p>
<p>(a). <strong>No cars arrive during a particular minute.</strong></p>
<p>Here, we want the probability that no cars arrive (i.e., <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">X=0</span></span>) in one minute.</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P(X = 0) = \frac{{e^{{-3}} \cdot 3^0}}{{0!}} = e^{{-3}} = 0.0498$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>(b). <strong>At least one car arrives during a particular minute.</strong></p>
<p>To find the probability that at least one car arrives, we can use the complement of the probability that no cars arrive.</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P(X \geq 1) = 1 &#8211; P(X = 0) = 1 &#8211; 0.0498 = 0.9502$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>(c). <strong>Four cars arriving in 2 minutes.</strong></p>
<p>In 2 minutes, the average rate would be<span class="katex"> <span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord mathnormal">λ </span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">3</span><span class="mbin">×</span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">2 </span><span class="mrel">= </span></span><span class="base"><span class="mord">6</span></span></span></span>. We want the probability of exactly 4 cars arriving in 2 minutes.</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P(X = 4) = \frac{{e^{{-6}} \cdot 6^4}}{{4!}} = \frac{{e^{{-6}} \cdot 1296}}{{24}} = 0.1339$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>So, the probabilities are: No cars arrive during a minute: <strong>0.0498</strong>. At least one car arrives during a minute: <strong>0.9502. </strong>Four cars arrive during 2 minutes: <strong>0.1339.</strong></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 12</h3>
<div><p><p>Let X and Y be two continuous random variable having joint pdf<br />
f(x,y) = c(x<sup>2</sup> + y<sup>2</sup>), 0< x <1, 0< y<1<br />
= 0 , otherwise.</p>
<p>Determine (a) the value of c. (b) P(x < 0.5,  y > 0.5).</p</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>Two continuous random variables X and Y must have a joint probability density function f(x,y) that satisfies:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_{{-\infty}}^{{\infty}} \int_{{-\infty}}^{{\infty}} f(x, y) \, dx \, dy = 1$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>Given the joint pdf:</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">f(x,y) = c(x<sup>2</sup> + y<sup>2</sup>), 0&lt; x &lt;1, 0&lt; y&lt;1<br />
= 0 , otherwise.</p>
<p>To find c, we integrate throughout the range 0&lt;x&lt;1 and 0&lt;y&lt;1.</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="minner"><span class="mord"><span class="mtable"><span class="col-align-l"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_0^1 \int_0^1 c(x^2 + y^2) \, dx \, dy = 1$$</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$c \int_0^1 \int_0^1 (x^2 + y^2) \, dx \, dy = 1$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= c \int_0^1 \left[ \int_0^1 (x^2 + y^2) \, dx \right] dy$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= c \int_0^1 \left( \int_0^1 x^2 \, dx + \int_0^1 y^2 \, dx \right) dy$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>Now,</p>
<p>Calculate each integral:</p>
<p><strong>Integral of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x<sup>2</sup></span></span>:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_0^1 x^2 \, dx = \left[ \frac{{x^3}}{{3}} \right]_0^1 = \frac{{1}}{{3}}$$</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><strong>Integral of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y<sup>2</sup></span></span>:<br />
</strong>Since <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y<sup>2</sup></span></span> is constant with respect to <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x</span></span>,</p>
<p>$$\int_0^1 y^2 \, dx = y^2$$<br />
<span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= c \int_0^1 \left( \frac{{1}}{{3}} + y^2 \right) dy$$<br />
</span></span></span></p>
<p>Now integrate with respect to <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y</span></span>:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= c \left[ \int_0^1 \frac{{1}}{{3}} \, dy + \int_0^1 y^2 \, dy \right]$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><strong>Integral of 1/3:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_0^1 \frac{{1}}{{3}} \, dy = \frac{{1}}{{3}} \cdot 1 = \frac{{1}}{{3}}$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><strong>Integral of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y<sup>2</sup></span></span>:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_0^1 y^2 \, dy = \left[ \frac{{y^3}}{{3}} \right]_0^1 = \frac{{1}}{{3}}$$</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>Combining these results:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= c \left( \frac{{1}}{{3}} + \frac{{1}}{{3}} \right) = c \cdot \frac{{2}}{{3}}$$</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s"><span class="katex-mathml"><span class="mord mathnormal">c </span><span class="mrel">= </span><span class="vlist">23</span>​<br />
</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>The integral of f(x,y) across the region 0&lt;x&lt;0.5 and 0.5&lt;y&lt;1 yields the probability P(X&lt;0.5,Y&gt;0.5):</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P(X &lt; 0.5, Y &gt; 0.5) = \int_{{0.5}}^1 \int_0^{{0.5}} \frac{{3}}{{2}} (x^2 + y^2) \, dx \, dy$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= \frac{{3}}{{2}} \int_{{0.5}}^1 \left[ \int_0^{{0.5}} (x^2 + y^2) \, dx \right] dy$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= \frac{{3}}{{2}} \int_{{0.5}}^1 \left( \int_0^{{0.5}} x^2 \, dx + \int_0^{{0.5}} y^2 \, dx \right) dy$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><strong>Integral of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">x<sup>2</sup></span></span>:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_0^{{0.5}} x^2 \, dx = \left[ \frac{{x^3}}{{3}} \right]_0^{{0.5}} = \frac{{(0.5)^3}}{{3}} = \frac{{0.125}}{{3}} = \frac{{1}}{{24}}$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><strong>Integral of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y<sup>2</sup></span></span>:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_0^{{0.5}} y^2 \, dx = y^2 \cdot 0.5 = \frac{{y^2}}{{2}}$$</span>​​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>Thus, we have:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= \frac{{3}}{{2}} \int_{{0.5}}^1 \left( \frac{{1}}{{24}} + \frac{{y^2}}{{2}} \right) dy$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>Now integrate with respect to <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y</span></span>:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= \frac{{3}}{{2}} \left[ \int_{{0.5}}^1 \frac{{1}}{{24}} \, dy + \int_{{0.5}}^1 \frac{{y^2}}{{2}} \, dy \right]$$</span></span></span></p>
<p>Evaluate each part:</p>
<p><strong>Integral of 1/24<span class="katex"><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_{{0.5}}^1 \frac{{1}}{{24}} \, dy = \frac{{1}}{{24}} \cdot \left(1 &#8211; 0.5\right) = \frac{{1}}{{24}} \cdot 0.5 = \frac{{1}}{{48}}$$</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p><strong>Integral of <span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">y<sup>2</sup></span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>:</strong></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$\int_{{0.5}}^1 \frac{{y^2}}{{2}} \, dy = \frac{{1}}{{2}} \int_{{0.5}}^1 y^2 \, dy = \frac{{1}}{{2}} \cdot \left[ \frac{{y^3}}{{3}} \right]_{{0.5}}^1$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= \frac{{1}}{{2}} \cdot \left( \frac{{1^3}}{{3}} &#8211; \frac{{(0.5)^3}}{{3}} \right) = \frac{{1}}{{2}} \cdot \left( \frac{{1}}{{3}} &#8211; \frac{{0.125}}{{3}} \right)$$</span></span></span></p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= \frac{{1}}{{2}} \cdot \frac{{0.875}}{{3}} = \frac{{0.875}}{{6}} = \frac{{7}}{{48}}$$</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>Combine these results:</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$= \frac{{3}}{{2}} \left( \frac{{1}}{{48}} + \frac{{7}}{{48}} \right) = \frac{{3}}{{2}} \cdot \frac{{8}}{{48}} = \frac{{3}}{{2}} \cdot \frac{{1}}{{6}} = \frac{{3}}{{12}} = \frac{{1}}{{4}}$$</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<p>So,</p>
<p><span class="katex-display"><span class="katex"><span class="katex-mathml">$$P(X &lt; 0.5, Y &gt; 0.5) = \frac{{1}}{{4}}$$</span><span class="katex-html" aria-hidden="true"><span class="base"><span class="mord"><span class="mfrac"><span class="vlist-t vlist-t2"><span class="vlist-r"><span class="vlist-s">​</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
</div>
<h3>Question 13</h3>
<div><p><p>Write short notes on any two:</p>
<ol>
<li>Random variable and probability distribution</li>
<li>Five number summary</li>
<li>Sampling error.</li>
</ol</p></div><div><strong>Answer:</strong><br><style>body .mathjax_wrap{width: 100%;overflow-x: scroll;margin-bottom:10px;}</style><p>a.<strong> Random variable and Probability distribution</strong> :</p>
<p>Random variable:<br />
The numerical result of a random phenomena is called a random variable. It can have several values, each of which has a corresponding probability. There are two categories of random variables:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Discrete Random Variable</span> : A countable number of different values can be assigned to a discrete random variable, such as the number of heads that appear when a coin is flipped several times.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Continuous Random Variable</span> : A continuous random variable, such as an individual&#8217;s height, can have an infinite number of values within a certain range.</li>
</ul>
<p>Probability distribution :<br />
A probability distribution explains the assignment of probabilities to a random variable&#8217;s potential values. It has two possible representations:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Probability Mass Function (PMF)</span> : When applied to discrete random variables, the Probability Mass Function (PMF) gives the likelihood of each potential value.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Probability density function (PDF)</span> : The probability that a continuous random variable will fall within a specific range is described by the probability density function (PDF).</li>
</ul>
<p>b. <strong>Five Number Summary :<br />
</strong></p>
<p>A descriptive statistic that gives a brief summary of the distribution of a dataset is the Five Number Summary. It contains five essential values:</p>
<ul style="list-style-type: square;">
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Minimum</span>: The dataset&#8217;s smallest value.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">First Quartile (Q1)</span>: The median, or 25th percentile, of the dataset&#8217;s lower half.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">The median (Q2)</span>: which represents the 50th percentile, is the dataset&#8217;s middle value when arranged</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Third Quartile (Q3)</span>: The median, or 75th percentile, of the dataset&#8217;s top half.</li>
<li><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Maximum</span>: The dataset&#8217;s highest value.</li>
</ul>
<p>Finding the data&#8217;s central tendency, spread, and any outliers is made easier with the help of the Five Number Summary. A box plot, which shows the quartiles and draws attention to the data&#8217;s range, is frequently used to visualize it.</p>
<p>c. <strong>Sampling error</strong> :<br />
The discrepancy between the sample statistic (such as the sample mean) and the population parameter (such as the population mean) that the statistic actually measures is known as the sampling error. When using a sample instead of testing the full population, there is intrinsic variability, which leads to this inaccuracy.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
</div>
</body></html>